submission_proverb_1.meaning: Human beings are never without a fault

submission_proverb_2.content: Abeesadii lix jir kugu qaniintaa lixdan jir bay kugu dishaa.
submission_proverb_2.meaning: A snake-bite received at the age of six kills you at the age of sixty (i.e. evil lingers a long time).

submission_proverb_3.content: Abkay dooli dilow, dad nool maas u dahaa?.
submission_proverb_3.meaning: My father has killed a mouse, will he fail to kill a man (people)?. Said about a coward who pretends to be brave.

submission_proverb_4.meaning: The world is like a shadow in the morning it is turned towards one direction, in the evening towards the opposite one (i.e. it is changeable).

submission_proverb_6.meaning: Do not speak (do not serve for ) a mouth that is present (i.e. one should not speak on behalf of a person who is present).

submission_proverb_7.content: Af macaan garan macaan baa dhaanta
submission_proverb_7.meaning: A sweet ( i.e. generous) hand is better than a sweet ( i.e. generous with promises) mouth.

submission_proverb_8.meaning: A living mouth does not give up talk

submission_proverb_9.meaning: Oh mouth, you have eaten something, now keep quiet (i.e. do not object to he who has fed you).

submission_proverb_10.content: Allow, nimaan wax ogayn ha cadaabin
submission_proverb_10.meaning: . Oh Allah, do not punish a man who sins through ignorance.

submission_proverb_11.content: Ama afeef hore lahow, ama adkeysi dambe lahow.
submission_proverb_11.meaning: Either refuse (to do something) at once or put up with it later.

submission_proverb_12.content: Ama leg ahay, ama lug ahay
submission_proverb_12.meaning: Catch hold of a brisket or at least a leg (because even a bad thing is better than nothing).

submission_proverb_13.content: Ama talo keen ahow, ama talo raac ahow.
submission_proverb_13.meaning: Either propose something yourself or agree to what is proposed by others.

submission_proverb_14.content: Ama waa la muuqdaa, ama waa la maqnaada.
submission_proverb_14.meaning: Either be visible or be absent (.i.e. either do a job well or do not set about it at all).

submission_proverb_15.meaning: The absence of knowledge is the absence of light.

submission_proverb_16.content: Arrini madax la qabtay leedahaye mijo la qabto ma leh.
submission_proverb_16.meaning: A problem can be seized (only) by its head, one cannot seize it by its tail (ankel).

submission_proverb_17.meaning: A wrong (bad) decision is worse than a drought.

submission_proverb_18.meaning: One should neither be late for the wedding nor stay too long at it.

submission_proverb_19.content: Awrba awrka ka horreeya ayuu saanqaadkiisa leeyahay.
submission_proverb_19.meaning: A camel (in caravan) follows the tracks of the leading camel.

submission_proverb_20.content: Awr awr wado iyo nin naagi waddo midna kaama baydho
submission_proverb_20.meaning: You cannot evade the camel which is driven ( in your direction) by another camel, nor the man who is driven (i.e. set on you) by a woman (i.e. a woman skilfully uses a man for pursuing her ends).

submission_proverb_21.meaning: The locust flew away but it left hardship.

submission_proverb_23.content: Baahi badan, baryo badan, iyo bukaan badanba waa laysku nacaa
submission_proverb_23.meaning: Both excessive needliness, too much begging and chronic ill-health can create undo resentment in others

submission_proverb_24.meaning: Not to fulfil a promise is just the same as not believing in God.

submission_proverb_25.content: Bakayle intuu bur ku jiruu bur kale daydaydaa
submission_proverb_25.meaning: The hare sits under one bush but looks out for another ( to which it might run if endangered).

submission_proverb_26.meaning: The cloth of the man who skirts about a clearing will not be torn by a tree ( i.e. a cautious person will avoid troubles).

submission_proverb_27.content: Baqal fardo la daaqday faras bay is mooddaa
submission_proverb_27.meaning: . If a mule grazes with horses it thinks that it is also a horse.

submission_proverb_28.meaning: I do not eat carrion. I drink soup made of carrion. Said about a bigot

submission_proverb_29.meaning: Do no reject me until you know me well (i.e. one should not be judged by appearances). This goes back to a tale about an ugly but brave young man who was unsuccessfully wooing a girl. She preferred a handsome but as it turned out cowardly man.

submission_proverb_30.meaning: One does not mourn so bitterly over a (lost) she-goat ( there is obviously a more serious hidden reason).

submission_proverb_31.meaning: One fat piece of meat spoils many other pieces.

submission_proverb_32.meaning: The herd of a man who knows only one place (i.e. pasture) does not grow. Another interpretation. The herd of a man who takes care only of his own animals does not grow ( because in any disater no one would help him.

submission_proverb_33.content: Baryo badan iyo bukaan badanba waa laysku nacaa
submission_proverb_33.meaning: . Beggars and ailing people are disliked equally.

submission_proverb_34.meaning: A liar settles his witness in a faraway place (i.e. he calls as witness someone who is not able to come.

submission_proverb_35.meaning: The truth will not catch up with a runaway lie.

submission_proverb_36.meaning: A lie leaves no trace (i.e. it has no weight).

submission_proverb_37.content: Beenlow nin dhintay iyo nin dheer ayuu marqaati u qabsadaa.
submission_proverb_37.meaning: A liar calls as witness one who is either dead ord far away.

submission_proverb_38.content: Beentaada hore runtaada danbay u baas baxdaa
submission_proverb_38.meaning: . Your previous lie damages your present truth.

submission_proverb_39.content: Been sheeg, laakin been run u eg sheeg.
submission_proverb_39.meaning: Tell lies, but let your lies resemble the truth.

submission_proverb_40.content: Belaayo intay kaa maqan tahay, qayrkaa bay ku maqan tahay
submission_proverb_40.meaning: If misfortune does not come to you it comes to somebody else ( somebody of your age).

submission_proverb_41.content: Belaayo ka-hor-tag moyee ka-dabo-tag ma leh
submission_proverb_41.meaning: Misfortune can be caught only from the front, it cannot be caught from behind (i.e. one can avert misfortune, but cannot control it if it has already happened).

submission_proverb_42.content: Belaayo kaa sii jeedda layskuma soo jeediyo.
submission_proverb_42.meaning: If a trouble shows its back, do not force it to show its face.

submission_proverb_43.content: Belo ama il la'ayd, ama lug la'ayd
submission_proverb_43.meaning: A wicked man is lacking either one eye or one leg ( which means he cannot damage the people round him in full measure).

submission_proverb_44.meaning: A bald spot reveals itself unexpectedly. Said about an unexpected trouble.

submission_proverb_45.content: Bilsaddex gurigaagana way kaa kexeysaa, guri kalana kuma gaarsiiso
submission_proverb_45.meaning: A young moon (a moon which was born three days ago) will take you out of your own house but it will not take you to somebody else's ( because it does not shine long). This means, no good will come of a hasty decisions.

submission_proverb_46.meaning: Dead-water is moved by running water.

submission_proverb_47.content: Biyo intaysan ku soo gaarin ayaa layska moosaa.
submission_proverb_47.meaning: Make a dam before the flows.

submission_proverb_48.content: Biyo meel godan bay isugu tagaan.
submission_proverb_48.meaning: Water flows to a low place.

submission_proverb_49.meaning: One drinks enough water only from one's own palms.

submission_proverb_50.content: Booraan hadimo ha qodin, ku dhici doontaana mooye
submission_proverb_50.meaning: If you dig a (deadly) hole for somebody, be careful not to fail into it yourself.

submission_proverb_51.content: Caado la gooyey caro Allay leedahay

submission_proverb_52.content: Cadowgaaga caano mac ayaa la siiyaa
submission_proverb_52.meaning: An enemy should be treated to fresh milk (i.e. should be treated as a dear guest in order to lessen his vigilance).

submission_proverb_53.content: Cagtii joogsan weyda, mar bay ceeb la kulantaa.
submission_proverb_53.meaning: The restless foot comes across trouble (shame).

submission_proverb_54.content: Canjeelo siday u kala korreyso ayaa loo cunaa
submission_proverb_54.meaning: . As the pancakes are piled, so they should be eaten.

submission_proverb_55.content: Calool dheregsani calool baahan kama naxdo
submission_proverb_55.meaning: A filled stomach does not sympathise with an empty one.

submission_proverb_56.content: Caano aan fiiqsi loo dhamin iyo hadal aan fiiro loo odhan feedhahaaga ayay wax yeelaan
submission_proverb_56.meaning: Milk which is gulped and words which are said rashly will hurt your ribs ( in the first case they will ache from coughing, in the second from a beating).

submission_proverb_57.meaning: When milk spills one tries to save the last drop at least ( catches milk by its tail).

submission_proverb_58.content: Carruuri haddii aad kuftid way kugu qososhaa
submission_proverb_58.meaning: When a grown-up falls, children laugh.

submission_proverb_59.meaning: Childhood is a grudge, which will be forgotten in time. Said to a child who is eager to become adult.

submission_proverb_60.meaning: He who has drunk your sour milk (i.e. whom you have reared) knows how to offend you deeply.

submission_proverb_61.content: Cimrigaagoo dheeraadaa geel dhalayuu ku tusaa.
submission_proverb_61.meaning: If you live long you will see how the camels are born. This is a city proverb, since the calving of camels is a normal thing for a nomad.

submission_proverb_62.meaning: An old man should not disgrace himself (one's old age should not be seen off with disgrace.

submission_proverb_63.meaning: Enmity is never small (i.e. each enemy can bring trouble)

submission_proverb_64.content: Col kaa badan iyo biyo kaa badanba way ku hafiyaan.
submission_proverb_64.meaning: You will be drowned by two things pelty of water and plenty of enemies.

submission_proverb_65.meaning: What if we were to strike the enemy with a sling.

submission_proverb_66.meaning: Honesty is not treated with empty hands ( i.e. it always rewarded).

submission_proverb_67.content: Dab aan kullaylkiisa la arag dambaskiisa lagama leexdo
submission_proverb_67.meaning: Until you know how the fire burns you are not afraid of the ashes (i.e. until you know how the man is when he is angry you are not afraid of him when he is calm).

submission_proverb_68.content: Dab munaafaq shiday mu'min baa ku gubta.
submission_proverb_68.meaning: A fire lit by sinful man (a hypocrite) burns a sinless man (a good Muslim).

submission_proverb_69.content: Dad iyo duurba wax aadan filayn baa kaaga soo baxa
submission_proverb_69.meaning: You should expect from people and the forest what cannot predict.

submission_proverb_70.content: Dagaal wiil baa ku dhinta ee wiil kuma dhasho
submission_proverb_70.meaning: In a war sons (a son) are killed, but none are borned.

submission_proverb_71.content: Dagaal nin aan aqoon baa ku orda
submission_proverb_71.meaning: A men who doesn't know about war is likely the one who rushes ot it

submission_proverb_72.content: Dameerada tan ugu foosha xun ayaa ugu haraanti kulul
submission_proverb_72.meaning: An ugly she-ass kicks most angrily (i.e. ugly women are most capricious).

submission_proverb_73.content: Dameeri isku-halleyn bay hooyadeed dabada uga nuugtaa
submission_proverb_73.meaning: A foal quietly suckles a she-donkey from behind ( not being afraid of a kick).

submission_proverb_74.meaning: The camels went for water and a donkey skipped with them. Said about an excessively complaisant person.

submission_proverb_75.content: Damiin faro waaweyn baa wax loogu qoraa.
submission_proverb_75.meaning: For a muddle-headed pupil everything should be written in capital letters (it is difficult to ram something into a numskill).

submission_proverb_76.meaning: Gains are shameless (i.e. in striving for gains a man loses all sense of shame).

submission_proverb_77.meaning: One cannot think of gain and please one's pride.

submission_proverb_78.content: Dantaada maqaar ey baa loogu seexdaa.
submission_proverb_78.meaning: In striving for gains you will sit even on a dogskin. According to Muslim ideas a dog is a dirty animal, so after having touched one , the ‘defiled' spot needs repeated ablutions.

submission_proverb_79.content: Dawaco meeshay macal uga baratay ayay macaluul ugu baqtidaa.
submission_proverb_79.meaning: The Jackal who has got accustomed to fat brisket will die of starvation.

submission_proverb_80.content: Dawaco tallaabadeediina ka tagtay, tii Nebigana gaari wayday
submission_proverb_80.meaning: The jackal has changed its step but still does not walk like the Prophet (i.e. one cannot change oneself).

submission_proverb_81.meaning: The ground quakes under a rascal (i.e. it seems to him that he is pursued).

submission_proverb_82.content: Dhagax taabasho iyo tuujin waa isugu mid
submission_proverb_82.meaning: It is all the same to a stone whether you touch it or squeeze it ( i.e. it does not matter).

submission_proverb_83.content: Dhar aanad lahayni dhaxan kaama cesho
submission_proverb_83.meaning: Somebody else's clothes do not warm you.

submission_proverb_84.content: Dhar magaalo intii laga xirto waa dhowdahay, dhal magaalase intii lagu noqdo noqdo waa dheer tahay
submission_proverb_84.meaning: One can quickly put on town clothes, but it takes a long time to become a townsman.

submission_proverb_85.content: Dhegi meel dheer bay ku dhacdaa, dhagaxna meel dhow
submission_proverb_85.meaning: A stone flies (falls) near, a word (an ear) far off.

submission_proverb_86.meaning: it washeat that made the cooking pot boil ( it was a certain reason that made that person angry.

submission_proverb_87.content: Dheri ninkii ag jooga ayaa lafta kala baxa
submission_proverb_87.meaning: He who sits close to a cooking pot gets a good bone.

submission_proverb_88.content: Dhicisku inta birta loo soo siduu ka bakhtiyaa
submission_proverb_88.meaning: A prematurely born ( camel) can die before one brings a knife ( to slaughter it). Said when the slighest delay can damage a case.

submission_proverb_89.content: Dhubuq-dhubuq hore dhabanno-hays dambe ayay leedahay
submission_proverb_89.meaning: He who makes haste at firs twill clutch at his head afterwards.

submission_proverb_90.content: Dhurwaa kan ciya iyo kan aamusan, kan ciyaa roon
submission_proverb_90.meaning: A barking hyena is better than one which keeps silent ( it is less dangerous).

submission_proverb_91.meaning: A swine is cursed only because it is a swine. Said when somebody is treated with undue contempt.

submission_proverb_92.content: Doqon iyo *censur* nimay legdaan kama kacaan
submission_proverb_92.meaning: A fool and a woman will not get off the man they have brought fown.

submission_proverb_93.content: Doqon wixii casarkii lagu caayo ayay cishihii kugi caysaa
submission_proverb_93.meaning: How you curse a fool in the afternoon so will he curse you in the evening. This usually means One should not do anything with a fool.

submission_proverb_94.meaning: Oh fool, your fire is too hit. Said when a silly person offers his help one cannot even ask him to kindle a fire, he will burn everything around him

submission_proverb_95.content: Doqonta usha agteeda ku dhufo, hadday garan weydana gogga u geli.
submission_proverb_95.meaning: Threaten a fool with a stick and if he misunderstands you beat him.

submission_proverb_97.content: Doqoni meeshii lagu dagaalay waa ogeyd ee meel lahu heshiiyey ma ogeyn
submission_proverb_97.meaning: The fool knew where they fought but not where they were reconciled.

submission_proverb_98.meaning: A fool is not a kinsman ( i.e. one cannot rely upon).

submission_proverb_99.content: Doqoni xadhkaha lagu xidhayo xusulladay ku sidataa
submission_proverb_99.meaning: A fool brings the rope himself with which he will be bound.

submission_proverb_100.meaning: One cannot be cured of foolishness.

submission_proverb_101.meaning: God does not have mercy (on people), but is merciful (he inflicts many ordeals, but gives people all they need).

submission_proverb_102.content: Erayga alifka ku qalloocda al bakhra kuma tooso
submission_proverb_102.meaning: If you err in the first letter of a word, it will not become better by the last letter ( by the last sura of Koran).

submission_proverb_103.content: Fadhi iyo fuud yicibeed laysku waa
submission_proverb_103.meaning: One cannot sit at home ( i.e. idle) and enjoy yi'ib nut soup. Somalis usually go to remote and often almost inaccessible places to gather these very nutritious nuts.

submission_proverb_104.meaning: The arrow will not fall out of your body however hard you may shake (i.e. no excuse will help you if you have been exposed).

submission_proverb_105.content: Far kaa xumaatay filiq-filiq kaagama harto
submission_proverb_105.meaning: However hard you shake (your hand) a score (bad) finger will not fall off ( i.e. you cannot get rid of your shortcomings).

submission_proverb_106.meaning: . One finger cannot wash a face.

submission_proverb_107.meaning: A mere finger can't obscure the sun ( one can not hide the truth by deception alone

submission_proverb_108.content: Farta iyo meesha buktaa is og.
submission_proverb_108.meaning: The finger knows where you ache (i.e. it always touches the sore spot).

submission_proverb_109.meaning: A (Muslim) man of law will not go to paradise without his kin ( because their ties are very strong). Another interpretation A (Muslim) man of law will not go to paradise because of his kin ( whom he has favoured).

submission_proverb_110.meaning: The mother of a coward does not lose her son ( does not die without sons).

submission_proverb_111.meaning: Oh, coward, the victory was at hand ( but you let it go).

submission_proverb_112.meaning: A coward knows that he is talked about.

submission_proverb_113.content: Gabar guri ha kaa gasho ama god
submission_proverb_113.meaning: Only a (timely) marriage or death (a grave) can keep your daughter (from disgrace).

submission_proverb_114.meaning: You may kill an infidel (if he deserves it), but be just to him (i.e. be just even to your enemy).

submission_proverb_115.content: Gacmo is dhaafaa gacalo ka timaaddaa
submission_proverb_115.meaning: Love emerges when hands give something to each other.

submission_proverb_116.content: Gacmo wadajir bay wax ku gooyaan.
submission_proverb_116.meaning: One can tear something ony with two hands.

submission_proverb_117.meaning: If the hand which used to catch (i.e. steal) is chopped off, the stump will twitch (i.e. it will also try to catch something).

submission_proverb_118.meaning: He who comes late ruins the gathering ( because his out-of-place judgements prevent it from reaching the already co-ordinated decisions).

submission_proverb_119.meaning: A beard should be shown a beard (i.e. in a dispute an experienced man should be opposed by a man of similar experience).

submission_proverb_120.meaning: Death and justice affect all men equally

submission_proverb_122.content: Gari laban in kama wada qosliyo.
submission_proverb_122.meaning: A just sentence cannot make happy (make laugh), both sides at once.

submission_proverb_123.content: Geed walba in gubtaa hoos taal
submission_proverb_123.meaning: Under every tree there is something which hampers its growth ( burns it). This means everyone has his own troubles.

submission_proverb_124.content: Geeljire geela waa wada jiraa, waana kala jiraa.
submission_proverb_124.meaning: When the camels graze together each herdsman keeps close to his own.

submission_proverb_125.content: Geel laba jir soo wada mar.
submission_proverb_125.meaning: All the camels were two years old (i.e. once upon a time everybody was young).

submission_proverb_126.content: Geeriyi nin aanad garanayn iyo geeljiray ku roon tahay
submission_proverb_126.meaning: Death is good in a man whom you do not know and in a herdsman ( who is likely to be far away).

submission_proverb_127.meaning: Allah does not disgrace a brave man.

submission_proverb_128.meaning: The mother of a brave man soon loses her son (dies without sons).

submission_proverb_129.meaning: Cut off the cow's horn while (the knife is still hot).

submission_proverb_130.content: Guri ann hooyo lahayni waa lama degaan
submission_proverb_130.meaning: A home without a mother is like a desert (mother makes home trustworthy, happier and lovable; without her, it's dark, fearful and very horrible to live in)

submission_proverb_131.meaning: To an old woman who is sitting down, wrestling seems to be the most simple thing. (i.e. when one takes a detached view, every job seems easy.

submission_proverb_132.meaning: Too much talk doesn't not fill vessel (talkativeness with no reasoning is always useless)

submission_proverb_133.content: Hadal intuu uurkaaga ku jiro ayuu ammaan yahay.
submission_proverb_133.meaning: A word is yours while it is in your stomach.

submission_proverb_134.content: Hadal nin si u yiri, ninna si u qaaday.
submission_proverb_134.meaning: You tell one thing but he may hear another.

submission_proverb_135.content: Hadal nin badiyey ma wada odhan, nin yareeyayna kama wada tegin
submission_proverb_135.meaning: He who talked much did not tell all he wanted, and he who talked a little told more than he wanted (i.e. one should not talk much).

submission_proverb_136.content: Hadal waa mergi hadba meel u jiidma.
submission_proverb_136.meaning: A word is like sinew. It stretches in every direction.

submission_proverb_137.content: Haddaad dhimaneysid dhareerka waa layska duwaa.
submission_proverb_137.meaning: If you are dying, wipe off your saliva (i.e. try to die suitable.

submission_proverb_138.content: Haddaan la kala roonaan, roob ma da'o.
submission_proverb_138.meaning: Unless one of the debaters gives in, it will not rain (i.e. no headway will be made in the matter.

submission_proverb_139.content: Hadday degdegsiinyo door dhalaan, kaadsiinyana kiish lacagay dhalaan
submission_proverb_139.meaning: Haste can give birth to a bit of money ( a small benefit), patience to a bag of it.

submission_proverb_140.content: Hadday fooli timaaddo, gudi qarsiimo hadhay
submission_proverb_140.meaning: When a labour pains start, shame must be thrown off.

submission_proverb_141.content: Haddii geeriyi ku deyn lahayd, gabow baan ku daayeen
submission_proverb_141.meaning: If you have managed to avoid a premature death, you will not manage to avoid old age.

submission_proverb_142.content: Hal diideysaa geed ay ku xoqato wa weydo
submission_proverb_142.meaning: If a she-camel does not want to do something, she finds a tree against which to rub herself.

submission_proverb_143.meaning: When a she-camel sees a lion her milk disappears ( because of fear).

submission_proverb_144.meaning: A millipede will not limp because of one leg.

submission_proverb_145.meaning: Where there are no women, there is no home (no women means no shelter; therefore, as they are the main pillars of the society then without them there is no means of joyous life)

submission_proverb_146.content: Hilib waa nin waayay iyo nin dabada ku xirtay
submission_proverb_146.meaning: One man does not have meat, another man does not know what to do with it ( he sticks it to his buttocks). Said by a hungry hyena at the sight of a monkey with ted buttocks.

submission_proverb_147.meaning: A slip of the tongue does not count ( does not enter speech).

submission_proverb_148.meaning: To know something for sure, one would even part with a she-camel.

submission_proverb_149.content: Hunnu-hunnuna hadal ma aha, himbiriirsina wax arag ma aha
submission_proverb_149.meaning: Wispering is not talk, screwing up one's eyes is not a glance.

submission_proverb_150.meaning: Eyes in love do not dare to stare at each other (lovers' eyes are bashful)

submission_proverb_151.content: Ilko wadajir bay wax ku gooyaan.
submission_proverb_151.meaning: Teeth bite something only when they bite togheter.

submission_proverb_152.content: Intii calooshu buki lahayd cagtu ha bukto
submission_proverb_152.meaning: It is better to have an aching leg than an aching spirit ( stomach, i.e. it is better to do something despite tiredneess, than later to regret that it had not been done).

submission_proverb_154.meaning: A coward ( a man whose cowardice is betrayed by his eyes) is beaten with his own stock.

submission_proverb_155.meaning: If people support each other they do not fall.

submission_proverb_156.meaning: . He who brought the jinnee (the trouble) must take it away.

submission_proverb_157.meaning: One has to change many ats for the man who is incontinent (i.e. one has to be patient with an intolerable person).

submission_proverb_158.content: Kab iyo xaarkeed waa laysla tuuraa
submission_proverb_158.meaning: A shoe is thrown out together with the shit it has trodden on.

submission_proverb_159.content: Khayr wax kaama dhimee shar u toog hay
submission_proverb_159.meaning: In good times be ready for bad times ( because times always change).

submission_proverb_160.meaning: ( on the road) the one who has no shoes falls behind, not the one whose shoes are bad ( i.e. it is better to have something bad than to have nothing).

submission_proverb_161.meaning: A old man sees even with his skin ( his skin consists of eyes).

submission_proverb_162.content: Kud ka guur oo qanjo u guur.
submission_proverb_162.meaning: He drove the cattle from plague to glanders (i.e. went from one trouble to another).

submission_proverb_163.meaning: He is with you but not with you ( i.e. he only pretends to be your friend).

submission_proverb_164.meaning: Do not trust ( do not talk to) he who gossips with you about others and with others about it.

submission_proverb_165.meaning: A man's chest cannot hold two (different) things together ( i.e. it is impossible to think about two different things at the same time). According to the notions of the somalis, the chest ( as well as the stomach) is the main depository of the intellect.

submission_proverb_166.content: Labaatanjir intuu geed ka booduu talo ka boodaa
submission_proverb_166.meaning: A young man of twenty makes mistakes as if he jumps over a log ( i.e. as easily).

submission_proverb_167.meaning: One naked man cannot carry another naked man (i.e. one poor man cannot help another poor man).

submission_proverb_168.content: Laba kala bariday kala war la'
submission_proverb_168.meaning: If two men spend a night far from each other, neither one of them knows how the other one is now.

submission_proverb_169.meaning: A giraffe bone can only be broken against another giraffe bone ( a difficult problem can only be solved with adequate means).

submission_proverb_170.meaning: . One surpassses the man from whom one has learnt something.

submission_proverb_171.content: La jiifiyaana bannaan, la joojiyaana bannaan.
submission_proverb_171.meaning: It is level at the rod standing upright and it is level at the rod lying flat.

submission_proverb_172.meaning: In the rainless season dry grass is (rich) fodder.

submission_proverb_173.meaning: The short-eared sheep does not hear the complaints about the drought ( it forgetsabout the sufferings of others once it is full)

submission_proverb_174.content: Lax walba shillalkay is dhigtaa lagu qalaa
submission_proverb_174.meaning: A sheep is slaughtered on the deck on which she herself is standing (i.e. everybody gets according to his deserts).

submission_proverb_175.content: La-yeele ma hilmaamo, laakin yeele wuu hilmaamaa
submission_proverb_175.meaning: An offence is forgotten not by the offendeed but by the offender.

submission_proverb_176.content: Libaax nin aan aqoon baa lax ka rida
submission_proverb_176.meaning: Only he who does not know a lion ( and therefore is not afraid of him) can take a sheep from him ( i.e. sometimes ignorance can be useful).

submission_proverb_177.content: Madax ka kor meel la salaaxo ma leh
submission_proverb_177.meaning: Above the head there is nothing to stroke. This means, 1) There is limit to everything. 2) Theres is no appeal against the decision of a superior.

submission_proverb_178.content: Madax muuqda iyo mindi saawir ah midna lagama samro
submission_proverb_178.meaning: A (stupid) head and a blunt knife, if they are near at hand, will always prove useful.

submission_proverb_179.content: Manjo dhooqo midba mar baa la baxshaa
submission_proverb_179.meaning: One pulls one's feet (ankels) out of the mud one by one (i.e. one finishes one thing before beginning another.

submission_proverb_180.content: Mar i dage Alle ha dago, mar labaad i dagase anaa is dagay.
submission_proverb_180.meaning: If somebody cheated you once he is a fool (because by the fraud he shook your faith in him), but if he cheated you twice you are a fool.

submission_proverb_181.content: Markii aan tamar hayayna talo ma ahayn, maantoon talo hayana tamar ma hayo
submission_proverb_181.meaning: When I had strengh I did not have brains, now I have brains but do not have strength.

submission_proverb_182.content: Marti badan iyo baryo badanba waa laysku nacaa
submission_proverb_182.meaning: Frequent guests and much begging are disliked equally.

submission_proverb_183.content: Maroodiga takarta saaran ma arkee kan kale tan saaran ayuu arkaa
submission_proverb_183.meaning: An elephant does not see the gadfly which is sitting on it but sees the one sitting on another elephant

submission_proverb_184.meaning: A snake must be killed by a blow to its head (i.e. an enemy must be struck down).

submission_proverb_185.meaning: A man vomits not where he wants to but where he is forced to. This means Sometimes a man is not able to control his actions.

submission_proverb_186.content: Maxay ku nuugtaa, maxayse ka nuugtaa?
submission_proverb_186.meaning: Ah, what will he now suckle and with what?.This goes back to a tale about a hyena who bit the lips off a camel calf and the udder of a she-camel, and then shed tears, pretending to be concerned with the fate of the poor calf.

submission_proverb_187.content: Meeshaad madaxeeda tahay manjaheeda layskama dhigo
submission_proverb_187.meaning: Do not be legs where you are a head ( i.e. do not behave as a subordinate man).

submission_proverb_188.content: Meel il laga la'yahay haddaad tagto, il baa layska ridaa.
submission_proverb_188.meaning: If you come to the one-eyed people's country (place), pull out your eye.

submission_proverb_189.content: Meel lagaa jecel yahay haddaad ka tagtid, meel lagaa neceb yahay ayaad tagtaa
submission_proverb_189.meaning: If you leave the place in which you are loved, you will come to the place in which you are hated.

submission_proverb_190.content: Meel siday u taallo ayaa loola yaallaa
submission_proverb_190.meaning: As the place is, so conduct yourself in it ( as the place stands so stand in it).

submission_proverb_191.content: Meel waa laga muuqdaa ama waa laga maqnaadaa
submission_proverb_191.meaning: At your niche, either make your presence known or stay away (be active or better be absent)

submission_proverb_192.content: Miro gunti ku jira kuwo geed saaran looma daadiyo.
submission_proverb_192.meaning: One does not throw away fruit in the pocket for the sake of fruit on the tree.

submission_proverb_193.content: Mukulaal mininkeeda joogtaa miciyo libaax bay leedahay.
submission_proverb_193.meaning: A cat in its own house has lion's fangs.

submission_proverb_194.content: Mulac carruurta ciyaar bay ka tahay, isna waa kan af bax
submission_proverb_194.meaning: What is play for children is death for a lizard.

submission_proverb_195.meaning: The soul tells you to run as fast as you can (i.e. to save your life with all your might).

submission_proverb_196.meaning: To be without a woman is to be without life (this indicates the crucial importance of a woman's support)

submission_proverb_197.content: Naag waa guri ama god ha kaga jirto.
submission_proverb_197.meaning: (or) Naag ha kaga jirto guri ama god. “Your woman should be in the house or in the grave.”

submission_proverb_198.meaning: . He to whom you gave birth did not give birth to you (i.e. your child does not treat you in the same way as you treat him).

submission_proverb_199.content: Nin aad fadhi kaga adag tahay looma sare joogsado
submission_proverb_199.meaning: If you can overcome somebody when you are sitting, do not stand up.

submission_proverb_200.content: Nin aad kabtiisa toleysid oo kafantaada tolaya
submission_proverb_200.meaning: You are stitching for him sandals and he is sewing for you a shroud.

submission_proverb_201.content: Nin aanad saacaad ku baran sanad kuma baratid
submission_proverb_201.meaning: . The man whom you failed to know within an hour you will not know within a year.

submission_proverb_202.content: Nin aan baqin waa loo baqaa
submission_proverb_202.meaning: One fears for the man who is fearless ( i.e. who does not take care of himself).

submission_proverb_203.meaning: He who does not perspire ( i.e. does not toil) does not eat to fullness.

submission_proverb_204.content: Nin aan dhul marini dhaayo la'
submission_proverb_204.meaning: He who has not travelled in the world has no eyes.

submission_proverb_205.content: Nin aan ku furin doonin yuu kuu rarin.
submission_proverb_205.meaning: He who is not going to unload your camel should not be the one to load it.

submission_proverb_206.content: Nin aan shantaadu kaa reebin sharci kaama reebo
submission_proverb_206.meaning: the law will not save you from the man you have failed to save yourself from with your fist.

submission_proverb_207.content: Nin aan shaqaysan, shaahi waa ka xaaraan.
submission_proverb_207.meaning: For he does not work (even) tea is not prohibited (impure).

submission_proverb_208.content: Nin aan warankaagu gelin warkaagu ma galo
submission_proverb_208.meaning: He who is not afraid of your spear will not be frightened of your word.

submission_proverb_209.content: Nin aan waxa jooga garani waxa soo socda ma garto
submission_proverb_209.meaning: He who does not understand what is going on now will not understand what is going to happen.

submission_proverb_210.meaning: Everybody brings to the well a young (beautiful) she-goat ( so as to give the best impression).

submission_proverb_211.meaning: As a man eats, so does he work.

submission_proverb_212.meaning: Pain burns the who has it.

submission_proverb_213.content: Ninkii boqolka soomay oo bakhtiga ku affuray
submission_proverb_213.meaning: He fasted a hundred days but broke his fast with carrion.

submission_proverb_214.meaning: A sick man has a hundred advisers.

submission_proverb_215.content: Nin cimrigiisa dheerada geel dhalaya ayuu arkaa. (Banaadir)
submission_proverb_215.meaning: “A man prolonging his age sees a camel giving birth.”

submission_proverb_216.meaning: The sandals of a dead man are more valuable than he is (there is no benefit from a dead man).

submission_proverb_217.meaning: He who warned you, saved you (did not kill you).

submission_proverb_218.content: Nin is faanshay waa ri'is nuugtay.
submission_proverb_218.meaning: He who praises himself is like a she-goat which suckles herself.

submission_proverb_219.content: Nin fadhigaaga arkaya looma sare joogsado
submission_proverb_219.meaning: Don't ask for help from a man who sees you need it ( who sees you sitting, because he would already have helped you if he had wanted to).

submission_proverb_220.meaning: He who is not just does not succeed.

submission_proverb_221.content: Nin geed geli jiray geed looma galo
submission_proverb_221.meaning: You cannot hide behind a tree from a man who always hides behind a tree himself ( i.e. you canoot outwit him in his own manner).

submission_proverb_222.content: Nin gu'kaa weyni gu'baas kaa weyn
submission_proverb_222.meaning: He who is one year older than you has lived in need one year longer.

submission_proverb_223.content: Nin habar dhashay hal ma seegi waayo
submission_proverb_223.meaning: He who was borne by a mother ( i.e. every man) can't help making mistakes (can't help missing).

submission_proverb_224.content: Nin ilko weyni hadduu go'ayana, inuu qoslayaa la moodaa
submission_proverb_224.meaning: When a man whose teet hare too big, for his mouth is dying, people think that he is laughing.

submission_proverb_225.content: Nin intuu geed ka boodo ayuu talo ka boodaa
submission_proverb_225.meaning: Man makes mistakes (as easily) as he jumps over a log.

submission_proverb_226.meaning: The aggressive man ultimately encounters a more aggressive man

submission_proverb_227.content: Nin iyo naagtii colna ma aha, nabadna ma aha.
submission_proverb_227.meaning: A husband and his wife live together neither at war nor at peace.

submission_proverb_228.meaning: . The man who guards the sleep of others sheep not sleep.

submission_proverb_229.content: Ninkaad kabo ka tolanaysid kuwiisaa la eegaa
submission_proverb_229.meaning: If you are asking a man to stitch a pair of shoes for you, look at his own shoes.

submission_proverb_230.content: Nin kaa hadal badan dhaxalka aabbahaa ayuu kaa qadiyaa
submission_proverb_230.meaning: He whose tongue is more eloquent than yours, will deprive you of your father's inheritance.

submission_proverb_231.content: Ninkii qayrkii loo xirayow, soo qoyso adiguna.
submission_proverb_231.meaning: If somebody of your age is being shaved, wet your own hair ( get ready for the same trouble).

submission_proverb_232.meaning: The sleeping herdsman's cow calves a he-calf.This goes back to a story about two herdsmen, whose cows calved at the same time. One giving birth to a he-calf, the other to a she-calf. While the owner of the cow which had calved a she-calf was asleep, his companion substituted it for his he-calf. Somalis consider that a she-calf is better than a he-calf, since when it grows it will give milk and have calves.

submission_proverb_233.content: Ninkii tiisa daryeela tu kale ku dara.
submission_proverb_233.meaning: Only he who managers his own job can help with somebody else's.

submission_proverb_234.meaning: A wet man is not afraid of water.

submission_proverb_235.content: Nin rag ah haweentii ka adag, doqonna isgaa ka adag
submission_proverb_235.meaning: A good man may be controlled by his wife, while lesser man dominates his

submission_proverb_236.meaning: A patient man will get his share.

submission_proverb_237.meaning: If the blow missed you that does not mean that you may feel safe ( because another blow can be delivered).

submission_proverb_238.content: Nin soori kaa qaadday waa nin seefi kaa qaadday.
submission_proverb_238.meaning: A gluttonous man is like a a dead man ( as if killed by a sword).

submission_proverb_239.content: Nin Tuur lihi siduu u seexdo isagaa yaqaan
submission_proverb_239.meaning: . A hunchback knows how he should sleep (i.e. every man knows better than you what he needs.

submission_proverb_240.content: Nin waalan hadduu qoslo, nin fayownaa qosla
submission_proverb_240.meaning: When a fool laughs, even a clever man cannot refræn from laughting.

submission_proverb_241.meaning: . “A man who has eaten something becomes shy.”

submission_proverb_242.content: Oodo dhacameed siday u kala sarreeyaan baa loo kala guraa
submission_proverb_242.meaning: As the branches of a fence (gate) are piled up, so they should be taken down.

submission_proverb_243.content: Oodi qaadis iyo jiidis waa isla guri weyn
submission_proverb_243.meaning: . It makes no difference if you carry or drag a branch ( to make a fence) it will get to the same yard (house).

submission_proverb_244.content: Qabri qori-saarid mooye qori-ka qaadid ma leh
submission_proverb_244.meaning: One should take branches to the grave ( marking the buring place ), but should not take them away. This means, one should help a man in neeed, but should not ask him for help.

submission_proverb_245.content: Qawl nin weyn ka dhacay waa qolof geed ka dhacday.
submission_proverb_245.meaning: The word of a man is like a piece of a bark which has fallen from a tree ( bark does not go back to its place and man does not take back his word).

submission_proverb_246.meaning: He who divides something gets either nothing or too much.

submission_proverb_247.meaning: A person who doesn't sweat, does not get his/her fill

submission_proverb_248.meaning: He who warns in advance is not likely to kill you (The man who fore-warns you is like the one who saves your life; someone who gives you a verbal warning beofre starting any hostilities with you cannot be blammed for harming you afterwards. if one admonishes you before he/she does harm to you, is the one who must be listened with care and left alone in peace; otherwise you will share the blame with him/her if anything untoward happens)

submission_proverb_250.content: Qori iyo qiiqiisa waa laysla tuuraa
submission_proverb_250.meaning: To get rid of smoke, you also throw out a fire-brand ( i.e. together with a bad thing one throws out a good thing).

submission_proverb_251.meaning: He who walks slowly will not step on a thorn.

submission_proverb_252.content: Quud aan jirin qoryo u guro.
submission_proverb_252.meaning: There is nothing to cook yet, but he has started to gather brushwood.

submission_proverb_253.content: Rag waa raggii hore, hadalna waa intuu yiri
submission_proverb_253.meaning: Real men are the men of old, and real words are those they pronounced.

submission_proverb_254.content: Rag waa shaah, dumarna waa sheeko
submission_proverb_254.meaning: Men like tea, women like conversation.

submission_proverb_255.content: Rag haween ayaa kala hor mariya
submission_proverb_255.meaning: It's the women who make some men succeed where others fail

submission_proverb_256.content: Rag tag lama dhago ee wuxuu ku tago ayaa la tusiya.
submission_proverb_256.meaning: “One doesn't tell a man ‘go away' but one shows him something so he will go.”

submission_proverb_257.content: Rag waxaa u liita ma toshe, ma tashade iyo ma tashiishe
submission_proverb_257.meaning: The worst man is he who never sews, never consults and never economizes ( There is no social value for he who can't consult his mind, can't manage his assets wisely or can't help himself otherwise)

submission_proverb_259.content: Runi rag waa ka nixisaa, waxse ma yeesho
submission_proverb_259.meaning: Truth can frighten a man, but it does not harm him.

submission_proverb_260.content: Run iyo ilkaba waa la caddeeyaa
submission_proverb_260.meaning: Truth and teeth should both be polished.

submission_proverb_261.content: Saddex baa rag ugu liita ma-toshe, ma-tashade iyo ma-tashiishe
submission_proverb_261.meaning: Saddex baa rag ugu liita ma-toshe, ma-tashade iyo ma-tashiishe Of all men, three types are the worst he who does not know how to sew (clothes for himself), he who does not know how to get (clothes) and he who does not know how to take care ( of them).

submission_proverb_262.content: Saddex waa layku nacaa baryo badan, bukto badan iyo baahi badan
submission_proverb_262.meaning: Saddex waa layku nacaa baryo badan, bukto badan iyo baahi badan Three types beggars, ailing people and gluttons, are all disliked equally.

submission_proverb_263.content: Sagaaro laba tun oo la kala qalo ma leh
submission_proverb_263.meaning: The neck of a dik-dik cannot be divided in half ( it is too small). The dik-dik is a miniature antilope.

submission_proverb_264.content: Salaadi siday kuu qabataa loo tukadaa
submission_proverb_264.meaning: As you are placed when caught by prayer-time, just so pray.

submission_proverb_265.meaning: . Every prayer should be offered at its proper time.

submission_proverb_266.meaning: To advice good is true faith

submission_proverb_267.meaning: Each bird flies only with birds (bird) of its own kind.

submission_proverb_268.content: Sidaad dooneyso haddaad weydo, sidaad ka badin weyso ayaa la yeela
submission_proverb_268.meaning: If you fail to do what you want, do what you have to do.

submission_proverb_269.meaning: I had milked for you much milk but you have left me only a little. According to the somali traditions, after having been given some milk a guest must leave something for the host.

submission_proverb_270.content: Sidee xeego loo xagtaa, ilkana u nabad galaan?
submission_proverb_270.meaning: Is it possible to gnaw a hego and not break any teeth. Hego is the very hard fruit of one of the palm trees.

submission_proverb_271.meaning: You will never get rid of what you were born with ( it will not roam from you)

submission_proverb_272.meaning: . Allah Himself helps a simple man to find a good place for his camp.

submission_proverb_273.content: Sir-ma-qabe saab baa biyo u celiya
submission_proverb_273.meaning: For an honest man even a saab holds water. The saab is an openwork wicker frame for holding a water-jar.

submission_proverb_274.meaning: A deceiver never prospers ( a cheater never succeeds)

submission_proverb_275.meaning: Women's tricks are not something one is able to percieve.

submission_proverb_276.content: Soomaalidu been waa sheegtaa, beense ma maahmaahdo
submission_proverb_276.meaning: . Somalis can lie, but their lie will never become a proverb.

submission_proverb_277.content: Taladaan la ruugin waa lagu rafaadaa
submission_proverb_277.meaning: An unconsidered (unchewed) decision will make you suffer.

submission_proverb_278.content: Talo adigaa ku nool ee iyadu kuguma noola
submission_proverb_278.meaning: It is you who need advice, it does not need you ( therefore advice should be appreciated).

submission_proverb_279.meaning: The right decision does not come by itself (i.e. it has to be found).

submission_proverb_280.content: Talo walaal diide taagoogta ayuu kajabaa
submission_proverb_280.meaning: . “One refusing a sibling's advice breaks his arm.”

submission_proverb_281.content: Talo xumo tog baas bay kaa riddaa
submission_proverb_281.meaning: Bad counsel may cause you to fall into an abyss

submission_proverb_282.meaning: There is not yet a fire for the first dates (i.e. until one job is completed, one should not start another one).

submission_proverb_283.meaning: There is a stone in every date (i.e.something bad in every good thing). It may also mean that there is a hidden sense in everything.

submission_proverb_284.content: Tuug la qabtay talo ma leh
submission_proverb_284.meaning: Nothing can help a caught thief.

submission_proverb_285.meaning: One thief does not steal from another thief.

submission_proverb_286.content: Ushaada nin aad ka qaadan kartid ayaa loo dhiibtaa
submission_proverb_286.meaning: Give your stick to hold only to a man from whom you can take it away again.

submission_proverb_287.meaning: . “These youth taught their mother to give birth.”

submission_proverb_288.content: Waari mayside war ha kaa haro.
submission_proverb_288.meaning: You will not remain (on earth) let a good memory of you remain.

submission_proverb_289.content: Waayeel warkiisa kaftan buu ku dhammeystaa
submission_proverb_289.meaning: A grown-up ma concludes his speech with a joke.

submission_proverb_290.content: Wadiiqada yari waddada weyn bay kugu riddaa
submission_proverb_290.meaning: A small path will take you to a big road.

submission_proverb_291.content: Waraf iyo shimbiro war isuma hayaan.
submission_proverb_291.meaning: The sling feels no animosity towards the birds (i.e. it kills them not through animosity, but by the will of its owner).

submission_proverb_292.meaning: News hurries to a meeting place (i.e. secrets become known).

submission_proverb_293.content: War la qabaa xiiso ma leh
submission_proverb_293.meaning: What is known is not interesting.

submission_proverb_294.meaning: what will ruin you is what you have got accustomed.

submission_proverb_295.content: Waxaad taqaan guurso, waxaad taqaan ha kuu dhashee
submission_proverb_295.meaning: Marry a woman you are sure of and you will have no doubt of your children ( i.e. you will be sure that you are their father).

submission_proverb_296.content: Waxaan ku cuninba waa la cunaa
submission_proverb_296.meaning: What does not eat you is eatable.

submission_proverb_297.content: Wax badso wax beel bay leedahay
submission_proverb_297.meaning: . If you want to get more, you will lose everything.

submission_proverb_298.content: Wax is weyddiini ma xuma ee wax is weydaarsi baa xun.
submission_proverb_298.meaning: It is not bad to ask each other for something, but it is bad to dodge each other.

submission_proverb_299.content: Wax la arko carrab iyo ilkaa isugu dhow, iyaguna waa is qaniinaan
submission_proverb_299.meaning: Nothing is so close to teeth as a tongue and event hen thet sometimes bite it.

submission_proverb_300.content: Wax la qariyo qurun baa ku jira.
submission_proverb_300.meaning: In What one hides (from people) there is always something bad (a piece of shit).

submission_proverb_301.content: Wax qof la toosan baa qof la tuur leh
submission_proverb_301.meaning: What is straight to one man is crooked to another ( i.e. what is liked by one man is disliked by another).

submission_proverb_302.content: Wax rag kaa galay rako kaa gale
submission_proverb_302.meaning: What you give a man you will not get back ( it will stick with him).

submission_proverb_303.content: Weysha gowrac, dibigu ha ku quustee
submission_proverb_303.meaning: . To get a bull, slaughter a heifer.

submission_proverb_304.meaning: Every rowdy will meet a man who can master him.

submission_proverb_305.content: Wixii araggiisu ku deeqo ayaa oontiisu ku deeqdaa
submission_proverb_305.meaning: What is nourishing in appearance is nourishing indeed.

submission_proverb_306.content: Wixii uurkaaga ku jira afkaa kaa xada.
submission_proverb_306.meaning: Your tongue steals what hides your soul ( stomach).

submission_proverb_307.content: Xaajo nimaan ogayni indhuhuu ka ridaa
submission_proverb_307.meaning: He who does not know the problem under discussion prevents its solution ( knocks out its eye).

submission_proverb_308.meaning: I like fat and I like liver. Said when somebody cannot choose between two things the simultaneus possession of which is not possible.

submission_proverb_309.meaning: To count (money, things) is not shameful.

submission_proverb_310.content: Xoolo rag farana ka tirsan feerana ka sisaaban
submission_proverb_310.meaning: Men's wealth is countable by hand and remembered by heart
